How lucky and privileged are we to be the children and grandchildren of a wonderful man like you, there really are not words that will ever do true justice to what you mean to us all. 
You’ve taught us to be fair, humble, kind, open, confident, independent; to be rebels when required and for some of us to let our inner hippie out. You have supported our dumb ideas, celebrated our success, and cried with us at our losses. 
More than anything you have, without any exception had our backs. Regardless of the situation you have always been there, the calm, cool, wise, voice of reason. 
You’ve never settled thinking your perfect, and we’ve all watched you grow and become a better version of yourself, you have never stopped learning always have a book (or 5 ) on the go and always up for a new adventure - like your first attempt at go karting yesterday. What a wonderful example you have been to everyone you have touched. 
Your love and devotion to our Mum is something we are all eternally grateful for, we all miss her so very much but we know how broken it has left your heart. 
Personally you have been my work mentor, my boss a coach and a leader to look up to. You are the guide from which we all measure the greatness of a father and importantly a man. 
We wish you a truly spectacular 80th birthday and life ahead, full of more adventures and cherished memories. 
You are so loved by so many And I’m proud to call you my Dad. Love you xxx
Still as gutted as the day you left, you are missed every day. Happy 50th Birthday Brother.

My best mate didn’t die from suicide. 
When people die from cancer, their cause of death can be various horrible things – seizure, pneumonia – and when someone dies after battling cancer, and people ask “How did they die?”, you never hear anyone say “pulmonary embolism”, the answer is always “cancer”. A Pulmonary Embolism can be the final cause of death with some cancers, but when an aunt of mine died from cancer, she died from cancer. That was it. 
When my friend died he died from “Depression”.
The word “suicide” gives many people the impression that “it was his own decision,” or “he chose to die, whereas most people with cancer fight to live.” And, because Depression is still such a misunderstood condition, you can hardly blame people for not really understanding. Just a quick search on facebook or Twitter will show how many people have little sympathy for those who commit suicide…
But, just as a Pulmonary Embolism is a fatal symptom of cancer, suicide is a fatal symptom of Depression. Depression is an illness, not a choice of lifestyle. You can’t just “cheer up” with depression, just as you can’t choose not to have cancer. When someone commits suicide as a result of Depression, they die from Depression – an illness that kills millions each year. It is hard to know exactly how many people actually die from Depression each year because the figures and statistics only seem to show how many people die from “suicide” each year. But considering that suicide accounted for one-third of deaths among people 15-24 years of age, and over a quarter of deaths among those 25-34 years of age we all clearly need to do more to battle this illness, and the stigmas that continue to surround it. Perhaps Depression might lose some its “it was his own fault” stigma, if we start focusing on the illness, rather than the symptom. My mate didn’t die from suicide. He died from Depression.
